The paper deals with the computation of approximate Nash equilibria in games, which is a central topic in game theory and algorithmic game theory. The use of polynomial time approximation schemes (PTAS) is a common technique in algorithmic game theory, and the paper presents a new PTAS for a specific class of games, namely two-strategy anonymous games. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also employs tools from the literature on Stein's Method, which is a statistical technique used in probability theory and mathematical statistics, suggesting that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are also likely sub-categories. The paper's focus on computing approximate Nash equilibria suggests that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) are also possible sub-categories.
